n option, but are unibodies from 2008 and 2010 comparable? Should there be a \"macbook-2010\" tag? Or both? IMO just \"unibody\" is ambiguous and \"non-unibody\" plain wasteful.','2011-04-22T18:50:13.623',1453,NULL),(915,433,0,'this should not be migrated to meta.so','2011-04-22T20:24:20.960',101,NULL),(916,433,3,'@Jeff OK, then can you provide a response to the request here?','2011-04-22T20:35:14.527',13,NULL),(918,442,0,'Anything specific I can help with? It sounds like most of it is sketched out but its down to making it happen.','2011-04-23T17:22:10.550',17,NULL),(920,496,0,'Yes - the unibodies are far more comparable than they are different. Thats why having that one distinction adds much more value than simply tagging every hardware model that gets bumped yearly. Of course - I much prefer the exact details being added or edited, but the value of tags is to distill and categorize for easy searching and clarification.','2011-04-25T14:52:00.100',5472,NULL),(921,500,3,'I dont think these tags are a good idea. As koiyu correctly pointed out, a tag must be workable as the *only* tag on a question.. these are not.','2011-04-26T09:15:55.010',101,NULL),(925,503,0,'Perhaps because the original iPhone was simply called the \"iPhone\"? I suppose an [iphone-2g] tag could be used if it must be explicitly defined.','2011-05-01T01:33:12.243',1346,NULL),(926,503,0,'I did end up using the iphone tag, but I observed it is also used on many iphone questions that are not regarding the original iphone.  It feels more like an \"any kind of iphone\" tag as opposed to an \"original v1 iphone\" tag.  And since the procedures and software used for popular tasks like jailbreaking are different and have different limitations on the original iphone, it would seem to merit its own tag','2011-05-01T02:30:24.003',6150,NULL),(927,506,0,'The title is a little confusing; when I first read it, I thought the question was asking for a list of all the terminal commands, and I read the answers just t